caption: Very mixed feelings about our night out at James.  My partner and I went to enjoy a personal dinner. We were seated near a personal heater outside that was put on low on a brisk night, not much of a problem since we had our coats on but did not know it could go higher.  We sat and got our orders in quickly, yet we were reminded 30 mins in that our order was not effectively put in so that we would wait longer. An additional 15 mins pass, we were then served our hot dishes of pasta & broccoli first...then to be served later our salad dish. The dishes were clearly rushed based on taste but nonetheless tasty.  As clients we would have appreciated an acknowledgement of our wait, even if that included a 3$ cookie on the house for dessert.  Which we ordered nonetheless and was simply just a dry reheated cookie.  There is a 15% guaranteed gratuity, regardless of the service added on the bill yet our waitress still showed us the iPad if we wanted to add more.  We do not understand what the service industry must have suffered during this pandemic, yet bad service and just an organized evening for us doesn't justify it.  Wouldn't return just yet, yet wouldn't suggest to my friends heading on an intimate dinner.
A pleasant outdoor dining experience. Food was delicious and served quickly. Very cute place on the corner in an otherwise residential neighborhood. Wouldn't hesitate to return.

The food is still excellent but the dining experience could be a lot better. Went for outside dining dinner over the weekend. The heaters are barely warm, the servers don’t open water or wine bottles, just drop them at the table with cups for you to serve yourself, and the food is served in take out containers with awkward little wooden forks. I had to ask for a proper plate and what was brought was a 6” paper plate. All ordering is done via app. The servers just quickly drop things off and leave. The whole experience just felt cold and uninviting and certainly over the top if it’s all being done in the name of Covid precautions.  Many other restaurants are still using plates and proper flatware in the very least. The food was good enough to return but not for awhile... once this is all over perhaps.

Perhaps if our first time eating here wasn't for a chilly Valentine's evening dinner in the middle of winter during a pandemic, this review (and our rating) would be different. But it was. First the one positive...the two service professionals who were at the helm that night couldn't have done more to make the best of obviously very challenging circumstances. Hats off to them both. Now the several downsides...at a place this pricey, you can't have any outside tables with no heat lamp. We had to move mid-meal after a covered table for two with a heater opened up. But this could've been forgiven had the food been special. It wasn't. For $95 per person prix fix, we got a small, luke warm, so-so trout dish (that was so smoked it could've just as well had been salmon), a tiny portion of short rib over a mash all served room temp/cold, and a mushroom dish with dried out rice and a missing ingredient of pecorino, also served underheated. The highlight of the meal was a large piece of chocolate pound cake, not because it was that good but because we were still hungry and it at least helped to quell the pangs. It was obvious that we were eating pre-prepared and pre-plated food that had been inadequately reheated. And the menu was wrong...a cold winter's night screams for hot comfort food. Again, service aside, we expected more from James, especially at these prices.
The absolute BEST bone broth!!!  I love James, have been going for years, and am so happy they deliver their delicious meals during COVID.  Cannot wait to return to indoor dining!

I really debated about leaving this review, because of covid, and really tried to give them the benefit of the doubt. Unfortunately, everything about our brunch experience today was at best "meh". I understand having to shift experiences around in having to accommodate covid regulations, and that's fine, but the lack of transparency, and frankly, outright exploitation is not ok. First of all, when I arrived shortly before noon for brunch with a friend, I was told that I cannot be seated unless I have a reservation (unbeknownst to me, my friend made one) - when I mentioned that the website didn't offer any option to make a reservation the lackadaisical response was "yeah, we need to update our website" - ok, it's officially 2021, why isn't that on your website already?  Now, mind you, it's 27° F outside at this time, none of the heat lamps have been turned on yet, and all the chairs are made of metal - yeah. Turns out, most of the ceiling-mounted heat lamps in their outdoor huts are too far away to actually warm anyone up, so fail to see the purpose or expense of keeping them running - whatever. They offered to bring us some blankets, which were actually quite nice and made all the difference in helping to tolerate the outdoor cold.  Now, because of covid regulations, you're expected to scan the QR code at the table to load the menu - and then place your order for "pickup" on their chownow restaurant store, and indicate which table you're sitting at when you check out. Yes - you're expected to pay in advance for your order. Sure, we get it. Makes sense. Between the two of us we ordered a cup of coffee, the Little Gems salad, Market Greens side salad, and a bowl of their Creamy Polenta. The coffee arrived first, lukewarm, and only 2/3rd full, even though I specifically did NOT check off "extra room for milk" - which they brought out in a tiny little plastic sauce container you would normally expect to find ketchup. Nothing else came out - no spoon/stirrer, no sweetener of any kind - ok. I politely asked if they have a spoon or sweetener they could bring out and received a reluctant "ok" scoffed at me.  Now, the polenta was pretty good, enjoyed the texture and the chive pesto-like topping, overall, would probably order this again. The Market Greens side salad was fresh, if somewhat bland.  The real kicker, however, was when they brought out the Little Gems salad, which we specifically ordered because the menu description indicated "crispy sunchokes" - very much in season now. This salad was priced at $15. The salad that was supposed to be the Little Gems that we received was just the larger version of the Market Greens they brought out, for more than double the price. When we went searching for the sunchokes, we couldn't find them! We asked our server about it, they went to check, and then came out with a little plastic container filled with pepitas (not in the salad) and explained that the kitchen was out of sunchokes so they brought the pepitas instead - bizarre! This salad is NOT worth $15, especially without the sunchokes - otherwise, it's some fresh greens, sunflower seeds and olives. Nobody mentioned they were out of certain ingredients and nobody updated the ONLINE DIGITAL MENU THAT TAKES 2 MINUTES TO UPDATE to reflect the menu change (or the price, for that matter).  After we finished brunch, we felt the need to say something to the manager who began with all kinds of excuses about why we had a poor experience and why the salad was lacking a crucial ingredient. We countered that the expectation was set, and the restaurant was already paid, and they did not deliver what they advertised. As an act of atonement, the manager offered to make us another salad....and low and behold - IT WAS FILLED WITH THE CRISPY SUNCHOKES. What?!? This is shady af and a total exploitation of the clientele who patronize this establishment. Unfortunately, because of this shadiness, I will not be returning to The James. You have an obligation to be and do better - and instead of being honest, you were shady.

First experience at James - a big let down and very sketchy.  I ordered the Little Gems Salad which boasted sunchokes as the standout ingredient, and bc of COVID paid up front with mandatory service.  The salad came without sunchokes - basically just a green salad. When I mentioned it to the waitress, she said they are out and brought me some pumpkin seeds instead.   On my way out I told another staff I was disappointed and he said the manager could offer me another salad, but it will still be without sunchokes. I got the second salad and surprisingly sunchokes manifested on my salad!  This whole experience seemed dishonest - offering what you don't plan to provide, taking money for what you don't plan to provide, not letting the customer know...and then reverse! Magically providing what should have been provided in the first place.  COVID accommodation: The heaters don't have any effect as they are hung super high. The blankets are excellent.  On the bright side, the greens were fresh and I got two salads.

Longing for the days of a homey meal and genuine customer service  This week I enjoyed a milestone birthday.  I went back to my childhood neigborhood in Brooklyn to celebrate.  Prospect Heights has grow a bit over the decades and now is dotted with more restaurants, ice cream parlor and boutiques.  We landed at the James Restaurant, a quaint neighborhood spot with a menu that would rival many artisanal restaurants but a wait staff with the skills and manners of a Tasmanian devil.  First the food.  As we settled into our meal we were met with a mix bag of flavors and quality in preparation.  The chefs strength is meat not seafood.  The meat dishes (burger, hanger steak and short ribs) were seasoned, cooked and served to perfection.  By contrast, the seafood dishes we overcooked, dried out and lacked flavor (octopus, trout and scallops).  Next up the service. Over the course of the meal, the quality of the food and the ambiance of the restaurant was marred by spotty service and the ruddiest, most unprofessional and non-attentive wait staff.  As the first customers seated for the evening, we hungrily watched as the first seating of guests ordered, ate and departed.  When we asked about our meals,  waitress was belligerent  and instead of checking in with the kitchen about the food decided it was more important to discuss us with the other wait staff.  When asked again about the food, the waitress threw more shade and when confronted about her behavior made excuses through a thick layer of attitude. While the tense conversation was defused with our slender dirty blond waitress, the staff's posture afterward was to avoid the table and artificially add the gratuity to the bill.  😕 yes the entitled, ill-mannered waitress was unhinged from reality.  After shutting down gratuity surcharge down, my party departed and reminisced how we longed for the old days in Prospect Heights when you could get a delicious homey meal with a side order of warm and welcoming customer service.  I would not recommend this place.  With so many culinary gems in the neighborhood, service is a critical marker for setting these "gems" apart.  And, based on our experience with the slender blond waitress, the service at the James Restaurant is epically poor and warrants avoiding this place.

This place has no sense of decency to acknowledge an error, yet still serve cold food after so long and ultimately do absolutely nothing about it.  STAY AWAY!!!

We were a party of four, the wait was almost an hour. We were told 20 mintues when we walked in and they kept telling us five mintues more every five minutes so we would not leave I guess.  I had a very water downed bloody marry while waiting, I would not recommend that at all. Finally they sat us down and brought us the food we already ordered while standing at the bar. By then it was 3 pm, they finish lunch/brunch at 3:30 so I belive they wanted us in and out quickly.  I had the angus burger, the meat was average,  The French friez was way under cooked. Shame really to serve it in such condition, as it looked promising. The servers were busy wrapping up the shift, it was challenging getting their attention for a glass of water!  I assumed that since we waited patiently for around an hour they would wave the drinks we had while waiting to be seated but unfortunately  they even made us pay for the cup of coffee that one of us orderd.  Not sure I will come back, not impressed!
I can sum up this place in two words: "don't bother". Seriously, there's not much wrong with James, but there's really nothing to recommend it either.

Good food but slightly unimaginative brunch menu (just like any other restaurants; not worse). Somehow there's some dust in my water twice in one sitting. It's either really dusty in there or my eyes were sharp that afternoon.
Came here in search of a good hearty burger and found exactly what I was looking for. Great atmosphere, love it!
Had the trout was delish.
Great burger! Amazing food! Be a local and go to James right now!
The Angus Burger is delicious. The other brunch options on the menu seem great too. Will definitely come back in the future.
Great Angus Burguer! Cooked perfectly!! I didn't try, but the menu has great brunch options...
Excellent food and service. Went on a recommendation and wasn't disappointed.
Good food and fresh ingredient, with good restaurant decor as well
Awesome well prepared locally sourced menu. We had an awesome meal here.
Excellent brunch!
Nice.
Never disappoints

Food was extremely fresh and delicious. I usually don't care about whole farm to table thing, but this place really showed what is great local seasonal food! Decor and service and general atmosphere to match. Def coming back.

Finally managed to eat here after three tries, maybe because we arrived at 10:00. First two times there was an insane wait (like an hour) and since the place is on a residential block it's not convenient to pop over for a drink nearby to wait, plus they don't take reservations. I would like to give the bartender six stars. Terrific cocktails with great attention to detail. I enjoyed the meal and the food was very good, but it didn't blow me away. Plus, somewhat overpriced (eg "small plate" of ravioli had exactly ONE ravioli, though large, was fifteen bucks.) Hence, overall a four star. I would certainly return because it's very close to where we live, but need to go at off hours.

This place is charming, tiny and worth the wait.  The duck sausage is the stand out for me, maybe the best scrambled eggs in Brooklyn doesn't hurt their cause as one my favorite brunch spots in Brooklyn
Please tell me more. Im lost

Friends and I live for Monday Nights (Burger Night). The burgers are reasonably priced and delicious! Their wine selection is very vast. I am a huge fan of red wine - and their red selection is very diverse. As a regular - the staff has become family! They are AWESOME!  Brooklyn <3's JAMES!!!!!!

Very tasty local food, but lacks knockout dishes. Our table of five ordered all side dishes as starters. Green beans and brocolli rabe were well loved. Cold squash soup was good. Pork belly was lackluster. Risotto was flavor deficient. People liked the sea bass special. One person got the prix fixe menu and those were among the least liked dishes of the table. Desserts were good. Wait staff were awesomely helpful including by steering me away from the skate.

A traveling companion and I were delightfully surprised by a recent dinner visit to James in Brooklyn. Clean is very important to me, and in all ways, the dining room and surrounding areas were spotless.  We chose to sit at the bar, and the care taken in the handcrafting of our drinks - a marvelously refreshing, fresh mint-muddled, lemon ginger fizz (heaven on a steamy NY night), was indicative of the care taken in our overall service and dinners.  The garlic-oil roasted chick peas are a new favorite, and the grass-fed Angus burger lives up to its reputation and value. The neighborhood - and those locals we met while relaxing at the bar - charming. The James beautifully complements that charm.
One of my favorite go-to spots for happy hour or weeknight dinner. Delicious food, fantastic service, and a truly great & comfortable environment. Love James!
Wonderful restaurant tucked back in the neighborhood. Come early weeknights for half priced burgers, or on the weekend for fabulous cocktails and brunch - I recommend the lemon ricotta pancakes.
Great room.  Good food.  Nice waitstaff.  A wonderful addition to the neighborhood.
Excellent food in a comfortable environment.
Tip: Happy hour burger for $9.50 with $5 beers really hit the spot. 5:30-6:30pm only.

Burger Happy Hour, $5 Draft Beer Happy Hour, Sunday Suppers and a great Brunch. James makes it easy to find a reason to have a meal here...Cozy corner banquette seating as well as two top tables. Also seating at the bar. Everything on the menu is delicious. Good selection of wine by the glass or bottle at a reasonable price. Generous portions (especially on the Quiche) and perfectly done bacon....They also do a Huntsmen's Feast (various types of game in a tasting menu) once a year....

When it comes to brunching, there are a few qualifications for a great time: amazing cocktails, awesome service, great breakfast dishes AND wonderful lunch options. With a slew of nicely composed cocktails, from the classic bloody mary to an interesting black and tan, the cocktails are supreme. Dishes like pulled pork on a biscuit and stuffed french toast, along with a killer burger, cover food bases above and beyond. The 'ambience' is nice and the service is good. WINNER.

You can't go wrong with the knowledgeable cocktail-making bartender or the food (poached duck egg over pulled pork on a cheddar biscuit). If you want an off the beaten path, relaxed atmosphere and chefs/bartenders who know their stuff, do not pass this by!
Noisy if the band is playing but otherwise an unpretentious comfort food bar that makes for a pleasant evening
